value.value: This gene plays a role in both extracellular matrix assembly and epidermal development.

Human LAMC2 wild-type allele is located within 1q25-q31 and is approximately 59 kb in length. This allele, which encodes laminin subunit gamma-2 protein, is involved in both the development of the epidermis and extracellular matrix organization. Mutation of the gene is associated with Herlitz junctional epidermolysis bullosa.
Laminin subunit gamma-2 (1193 aa, ~131 kDa) is encoded by the human LAMC2 gene. This protein plays a role in both the organization of the extracellular matrix and the development of the epidermis.
This gene is involved in the modulation of both transcription and mRNA splicing.

Human WTAP wild-type allele is located within 6q25-q27 and is approximately 31 kb in length. This allele, which encodes pre-mRNA-splicing regulator WTAP protein, plays a role in the regulation of RNA processing.
Pre-mRNA-splicing regulator WTAP (396 aa, ~44 kDa) is encoded by the human WTAP gene. This protein is involved in the modulation of RNA processing.

This gene plays a role in the repression of HOXD gene expression.

Human HOTAIR wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 12q13.13 and is approximately 13 kb in length. This allele, which encodes HOX transcript antisense RNA, is involved in the negative regulation of HOXD gene transcription.

HOX transcript antisense RNA (~2 kb) is encoded by the human HOTAIR gene. This non-coding RNA plays a role in the repression of HOXD genes.

This gene plays a role in the regulation of nuclear receptor-dependent transcription.

Human PPARGC1A wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 4p15.1 and is approximately 149 kb in length. This allele, which encodes peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor gamma coactivator 1-alpha protein, is involved in transcriptional regulation mediated by steroid and nuclear receptors.
Peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor gamma coactivator 1-alpha (798 aa, ~91 kDa) is encoded by the human PPARGC1A gene. This protein plays a role in the regulation of gene transcription.
This gene plays a role in both chromatin modification and the positive regulation of transcription.

Human ASXL2 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 2p24.1 and is approximately 145 kb in length. This allele, which encodes putative Polycomb group protein ASXL2, is involved in both transcriptional regulation and chromatin modification.
Putative Polycomb group protein ASXL2 (1435 aa, ~154 kDa) is encoded by the human ASXL2 gene. This protein plays a role in both the activation of transcription and chromatin remodeling.
This gene plays a role in the regulation of autophagy.

A water-soluble organic solvent.  As an adjuvant antineoplastic agent, N-methylformamide depletes cellular glutathione, a key molecule involved in the antioxidation of reactive oxygen species (ROS) and other free radicals, thereby enhancing ionizing radiation-induced DNA cross-linking in and terminal differentiation of tumor cells. (NCI04)

Human CISD2 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 4q24 and is approximately 24 kb in length. This allele, which encodes CDGSH iron-sulfur domain-containing protein 2, is involved in both iron-sulfur binding and autophagy. Mutation of the gene is associated with Wolfram syndrome 2.
CDGSH iron-sulfur domain-containing protein 2 (135 aa, ~15 kDa) is encoded by the human CISD2 gene. This protein plays a role in the regulation of autophagy.
This gene is involved in embryonic pattern formation.

Human HOXC10 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 12q13.3 and is approximately 5 kb in length. This allele, which encodes homeobox protein Hox-C10, plays a role in embryonic axis determination.
Homeobox protein Hox-C10 (342 aa, ~38 kDa) is encoded by the human HOXC10 gene. This protein is involved in embryonic pattern specification.
This gene plays a role in both protein phosphorylation and Jun signaling pathways.

Human MAP4K3 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 2p22.1 and is approximately 188 kb in length. This allele, which encodes mitogen-activated protein kinase kinase kinase kinase 3 protein, is involved in the modulation of Jun signaling.

label.value: Mitogen-Activated Protein Kinase Kinase Kinase Kinase 3

value.value: Mitogen-activated protein kinase kinase kinase kinase 3 (894 aa, ~101 kDa) is encoded by the human MAP4K3 gene. This protein plays a role in the Jun signaling pathway.
This gene is involved in guanine nucleotide exchange.

Human SOS1 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 2p21 and is approximately 143 kb in length. This allele, which encodes son of sevenless homolog 1 protein, plays a role in both signaling and guanine nucleotide exchange. Mutation of the gene is associated with both gingival fibromatosis type 1 and Noonan syndrome type 4.

An episode during which the patient, usually a child less than one year, experiences a combination of apnea, color change, alteration in muscle tone, choking or gagging. This event can be frightening to the observer.
Son of sevenless homolog 1 (1333 aa, ~152 kDa) is encoded by the human SOS1 gene. This protein is involved in the mediation of guanine nucleotide exchange for RAS superfamily proteins.
The sound produced by tissue vibrations in the nasopharynx and pharynx secondary to partial obstruction of the upper airway.
A condition characterized by cardiorespiratory and neurological depression following birth.
A decrease in ventilation secondary to impaired signals from the central nervous system.
A harsh inspiratory sound during sleep.
An adenocarcinoma that arises from the nasal cavity and paranasal sinuses. Histologically it resembles intestinal adenocarcinoma. It is associated with lengthy occupational exposure to dust.
A very rare small cell neuroendocrine carcinoma that arises from the kidney.
A very rare small cell neuroendocrine carcinoma that arises from the nose and paranasal sinuses.

A rare chromosomal disorder characterized by trisomy of chromosome 14 in some cells in the body.  It manifests with intrauterine growth retardation, craniofacial abnormalities, failure to thrive, psychomotor delays, and mental retardation.
